    id: 'learning-theory-cognition-transfer', chapterId: 'plt5622-ch-01', domainId: 'students-as-learners', domain: 'Students as Learners',
    label: 'Learning Theory, Cognition, and Transfer', references: [ETS, INTASC, IES_LEARNING],
    questions: [
      q('A fourth-grade class holds persistent misconceptions before a science unit. Which planning step best uses schema theory?', 'Students interpret a new history topic only through an inaccurate prior idea. What should the teacher do first?', 'Elicit and examine prior knowledge, make the conflict visible with evidence, and connect the revised concept to an organized knowledge structure.', ['Begin with isolated vocabulary copying.', 'Avoid discussing prior ideas so they disappear.', 'Assign a final test before instruction.'], 'Schema influences how learners notice, organize, and retrieve new information; instruction should activate relevant knowledge and explicitly reorganize misconceptions.'),
      q('Which classroom routine most directly develops metacognition during multistep problem solving?', 'A student can complete a task with help but cannot explain how to choose a strategy. What teacher response best builds metacognition?', 'Model planning and monitoring, prompt the learner to name the strategy and evidence, and require reflection on when the strategy should change.', ['Praise speed without discussing reasoning.', 'Give the answer after the first error.', 'Require memorization of one procedure for every problem.'], 'Metacognition includes planning, monitoring understanding and strategy use, evaluating results, and adjusting deliberately rather than merely completing a task.'),
      q('Students solve fraction problems in one familiar format but fail when the context changes. Which instructional move best promotes transfer?', 'A learned reading strategy appears only on the worksheet used during instruction. How should the teacher promote transfer?', 'Use varied examples and contexts, compare deep structures, ask students to explain when the strategy applies, and gradually remove prompts.', ['Repeat the identical item format indefinitely.', 'Introduce unrelated topics without comparison.', 'Tell students that transfer should happen automatically.'], 'Transfer improves when learners recognize underlying relationships, retrieve the strategy across varied situations, explain its conditions, and practice independently.'),
      q('A learner succeeds on a complex task only while the teacher gives well-timed prompts. How should instruction proceed within the zone of proximal development?', 'During guided practice, a second grader needs a visual cue and one question to continue. What is the strongest next step?', 'Provide contingent support that enables success, monitor performance, and fade or adjust the support as independent control develops.', ['Remove every support immediately.', 'Complete the task for the learner each time.', 'Keep the same prompts permanently regardless of progress.'], 'Scaffolding is responsive temporary support for work a learner can accomplish with assistance; it is adjusted and faded as competence and self-regulation increase.'),
      q('Which use of teacher modeling best reflects social learning theory?', 'A class needs to learn how to disagree productively during discussion. What modeling approach is most defensible?', 'Demonstrate the behavior and thinking, direct attention to critical features, provide supported rehearsal and feedback, and reinforce successful use.', ['Describe the rule once without an example.', 'Wait for students to imitate peers by chance.', 'Punish every initial error without practice.'], 'Observational learning is strengthened by attention to a credible model, retention of what was observed, opportunities to reproduce it, feedback, and motivation.'),
      q('Which mathematics experience is most appropriate for many learners developing concrete-operational reasoning?', 'A teacher introduces conservation and equivalence to elementary learners. Which design best connects with their developing reasoning?', 'Let students manipulate and compare concrete representations, explain transformations, and connect those actions with increasingly abstract symbols.', ['Use symbols only and forbid models.', 'Ask students to accept the rule without evidence.', 'Delay all logical classification until adolescence.'], 'Elementary learners often reason more successfully about logical relationships when ideas are grounded in observable objects and actions before abstraction is increased.'),
      q('A teacher wants inquiry to produce conceptual learning rather than unstructured activity. Which design is strongest?', 'Students are exploring plant growth, but their observations are disconnected from the learning goal. How should the teacher scaffold the inquiry?', 'Pose a purposeful problem, activate relevant knowledge, provide tools and strategic prompts, require evidence-based explanation, and synthesize the findings.', ['Let activity continue without a question or synthesis.', 'Reveal every conclusion before students investigate.', 'Grade only whether the materials were handled quietly.'], 'Guided inquiry combines active construction with clear goals, productive constraints, evidence, teacher prompts, discussion, and consolidation of the intended concept.'),
      q('A teacher removes an unpleasant extra practice requirement when students meet a fluency criterion. Which behavioral concept describes the consequence?', 'Students begin a routine more consistently because completing it ends an unwanted monitoring step. What process is illustrated?', 'Negative reinforcement, because removal of an aversive condition increases the preceding behavior.', ['Positive punishment, because something was removed.', 'Extinction, because the behavior increased.', 'Classical conditioning, because no consequence followed behavior.'], 'Negative reinforcement increases behavior through removal of an aversive condition; it is not punishment, which is intended to decrease behavior.'),
    ],
